etymologies: late 17th century; earliest use found in John Bulteel (d. ?1692), writer and translator. Originally from French francisque from post-classical Latin francisca (636 in Isidore), use as noun (short for e.g. securis francisca Frankish axe) of feminine of franciscus Frankish

definitions: A type of battleaxe, varying in form, used by the ancient Franks.
